[{"location":"#ParabolicTrigonometry.jl","page":"ParabolicTrigonometry.jl","title":"ParabolicTrigonometry.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"ParabolicTrigonometry.jl","title":"ParabolicTrigonometry.jl","text":"Modules = [ParabolicTrigonometry]","category":"page"},{"location":"#ParabolicTrigonometry.cosp-Tuple{Any}","page":"ParabolicTrigonometry.jl","title":"ParabolicTrigonometry.cosp","text":"cosp(ϕ)\n\nThe parabolic cosine function cosp, related to cos and cosh. See G. Dattoli, M. Migliorati, M. Quattromini, and P. E. Ricci, arXiv:1102.1563 [math-ph] for a definition.\n\nThe parabolic cosine function satisfies\n\ncosp(0) = 1\nsinp(0) = 0\ncosp(ϕ)^2 + sin(ϕ) = 1\ncosp(ϕ)' = - 1 / (sinp(ϕ) + 2 cosp(ϕ)^2)\nsinp(ϕ)' = 2 cosp(ϕ) / (sinp(ϕ) + 2 cosp(ϕ)^2)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ParabolicTrigonometry.gudemann-Tuple{Any}","page":"ParabolicTrigonometry.jl","title":"ParabolicTrigonometry.gudemann","text":"gudemann(ϕ)\n\nThe Gudemann function, defined by tan(ϕ) = tanh(ϕ).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ParabolicTrigonometry.sinp-Tuple{Any}","page":"ParabolicTrigonometry.jl","title":"ParabolicTrigonometry.sinp","text":"sinp(ϕ)\n\nThe parabolic sine function sinp, related to sin and sinh. See G. Dattoli, M. Migliorati, M. Quattromini, and P. E. Ricci, arXiv:1102.1563 [math-ph] for a definition.\n\nThe parabolic sine function satisfies\n\ncosp(0) = 1\nsinp(0) = 0\ncosp(ϕ)^2 + sin(ϕ) = 1\ncosp(ϕ)' = - 1 / (sinp(ϕ) + 2 cosp(ϕ)^2)\nsinp(ϕ)' = 2 cosp(ϕ) / (sinp(ϕ) + 2 cosp(ϕ)^2)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
